0.body: ★★★☆☆ These notes have enough examples to make the topic clear. Zsh is a shell available on Unix systems. A shell is a CLI (command line interpreter) and, prior to 1970, was the only user interface available for computers; there were no GUI. Many Linux distributions come with Bash as the default shell. The command listed on this pages work for both Bash and Zsh; as they are based on Bourne Shell.
0.title: Introduction

1.body: Zsh : a shell available for Unix systems. Shell : it's a program that takes commands from a terminal and gives them to the Kernel (low-level part of an Operating System). Terminal : program that opens a graphical window from where the user can interact with the shell.

21.body: echo is the command used to display a line of text. It can be useful for scripts to create the user interface.
21.title: Hello World

22.body: echo Hello world! # => Hello world! In the example above, the first line is the command passed to the terminal. echo represent the command and Hello world! represent the parameter passed to the command. The second line is a comment . The # character indicates that the line should be treated by the shell like a comment and everything written on the line after the hash mark will be ignored. Comments are very useful for documentation. So, in the example above, on the second line, I used a comment # => Hello world! to indicate the output of the first line.
22.title: Simple example

23.body: Create a file on the desktop, for example, echo.sh and paste the following: #!/usr/bin/env bash echo Hello world! On linux, like Ubuntu, right-click the desktop and choose Open in terminal from the menu. At the terminal type: ./echo.sh The difference from the other example is that when running a script we have to insert a shebang. Precisely, the first line of the script is the shebang which tells the system how to execute the script. Note that shebang is also a comment.
23.title: Script example

35.body:
Built-in variables are variables provided by the shell. Here are some useful build-in variables: $? echo "Last program's return value: $?" $$ echo "Script's PID: $$" $# echo "Number of arguments passed to script: $#" $@ echo "All arguments passed to script: $@" $1 $2... echo "Script's arguments separated into different variables: $1 $2..." More than 9 arguments are also possible by using braces, e.g. ${10}, ${11}, ... pwd # Our current directory is available through the command `pwd`.
# `pwd` stands for "print working directory".
# We can also use the built-in variable `$PWD`.
# Observe that the following are equivalent:
echo "I'm in $(pwd)" # execs `pwd` and interpolates output
echo "I'm in $PWD" # interpolates the variable

52.body:
# use `man test` for more info about conditionals
if [ $Name != $USER ]
then echo "Your name isn't your username"
else echo "Your name is your username"
fi
# True if the value of $Name is not equal to the current user's login username Note # if $Name is empty, bash sees the above condition as:
if [ != $USER ]
# which is invalid syntax
# so the "safe" way to use potentially empty variables in bash is:
if [ "$Name" != $USER ] ...
# which, when $Name is empty, is seen by bash as:
if [ "" != $USER ] ...
# which works as expected

74.body:
Linux comes with useful commands that run from the terminal. To check where the commands are stored on your OS, type at the terminal: which date
# => /usr/bin/date /usr/bin/ is the location, on Manjaro OS, of all the commands that are showed in the following pages. Commands can also run in the background if an ampersand & is placed after a command. A background commands output is printed to the terminal, but it cannot read from the input. Run command in the background sleep 30 & Display command that runs in the background. jobs
# => [1]+ Running sleep 30 & The command sleep is executed in the background, and after 30 seconds the command will end. Bring the job to the foreground fg
# => [1] + 98656 running sleep 30 fg brings to the foreground the sleep process, if 30s have not passed, and waits for sleep to finish. Kill or pause the process Use Ctrl-C to kill the process, or Ctrl-Z to pause it If Ctrl-C is used after fg, the sleep process will end even if the 30s have not passed. If Ctrl-Z is used, then the sleep process will pause until it is resumed. Resume command # Resume a background process after it has been paused with Ctrl-Z
bg With bg the sleep process will resume and end when the 30s have passed.
74.title: Commands
